## 3. Demand-Side Factors Driving Oil Price Increases

### 3.1 Economic Recovery and Rising Global Demand

The global economic rebound following the COVID-19 pandemic has led to a significant increase in oil demand. As economies reopened, consumption in transportation, manufacturing, and energy sectors surged. OPEC forecasts a rise in oil demand by 6.1 million b/d compared to 2018 levels, with expectations of demand topping 100 million b/d by mid-2022 ([Capital.com, 2020](https://capital.com/crude-oil-price-forecast); [BusinessLive, 2022](https://www.businesslive.co.za/bloomberg/news/2022-01-09-oil-springs-a-surprise-with-bullish-rally/)).

### 3.2 Substitution Effects Due to Natural Gas and Coal Price Surges

The sharp increase in natural gas prices, especially in Europe and Asia, has led to higher oil demand as industries and power generation shift towards oil as a substitute fuel. Coal shortages in Asia have similarly boosted oil consumption ([Marca, 2021](https://www.marca.com/en/lifestyle/us-news/2021/10/24/617520d222601d10078b45ab.html); [Peakoil.com, 2022](https://peakoil.com/consumption/why-is-there-a-global-price-hike-in-the-oil-market)).

### 3.3 Depletion of Crude Oil Stock Buffers

In early 2017, a significant buffer of crude oil stocks had accumulated due to supply exceeding demand, which stabilized prices around $55 per barrel. However, subsequent supply cuts and rising demand have substantially depleted these buffers, increasing price volatility and sensitivity to geopolitical risks ([CaixaBank Research, 2018](https://www.caixabankresearch.com/en/economics-markets/commodities/what-behind-rise-oil-prices)).

---

## 4. Geopolitical and Market Sentiment Factors

### 4.1 Geopolitical Risk and Oil Price Volatility

There is a strong positive correlation between geopolitical risk and oil price increases, especially during periods of heightened uncertainty. Conflicts involving major oil producers or consumers, such as the Gulf War, Iraq invasion, and Russia-Ukraine crisis, have historically led to sharp price jumps ([Kilian & Zhou, 2019](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140988319303184)).

Oil is increasingly viewed as a hedge against geopolitical uncertainty, sometimes replacing gold as a safe haven asset due to its direct link to economic production and consumption ([Kilian & Zhou, 2019](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0140988319303184)).

### 4.2 Market Expectations and Speculation

Market sentiment, driven by expectations of future supply-demand balances, also influences oil prices. For example, rising tensions between the US and Iran elevated risk premiums, pushing prices higher even when physical supply-demand fundamentals were weak ([Capital.com, 2020](https://capital.com/oil-price-analysis-in-may-2020)).

Investment banks and brokers have raised oil price forecasts based on positive supply-demand momentum, further fueling speculative buying and price rallies ([Capital.com, 2020](https://capital.com/oil-price-analysis-in-may-2020)).

---

## 5. Regulatory and Structural Influences

### 5.1 IMO 2020 Regulation and Fuel Quality Standards

The IMO 2020 regulation, which prohibits the use of high sulfur fuel oil in marine bunkers, has forced a significant transformation in fuel supply chains. This has increased costs for shipping companies and affected oil product markets, contributing to price pressures ([Capital.com, 2020](https://capital.com/crude-oil-price-forecast)).

### 5.2 Refinery Utilization and Operational Costs

Increased refinery utilization rates, such as the US reaching 81.9% utilization in early 2010, have supported higher oil prices by absorbing crude supplies and increasing demand for refined products. High refinery operating costs also contribute to maintaining elevated oil prices despite fluctuations in crude supply ([Oil-Price.net, 2010](http://oil-price.net/en/articles/reasons-behind-oil-price-rise.php)).

